data.content:
This is the **C# 14 span overload resolution** breaking change.

## What happened

In C# 14, new built-in conversions from arrays to `Span<T>`/`ReadOnlySpan<T>` cause overload resolution to prefer `MemoryExtensions.Contains<T>(Span<T>, T)` over `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)` when calling `.Contains()` on an array.

`MemoryExtensions.Contains` **cannot be represented in a LINQ expression tree**, so the compiled expression throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by casting the array to `IEnumerable<T>` or calling `.AsEnumerable()`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);

// Option 3: cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);
```

Any of these prevent the span overload from being selected, keeping the expression tree valid.
